<paragraph id="8628475BFFBF850CFF13FC90FDD0FB84" blockId="24.[136,1451,842,1048]" pageId="24" pageNumber="235">
<emphasis id="B4E39B49FFBF850CFF13FC90FEE9FC14" bold="true" box="[189,294,878,904]" pageId="24" pageNumber="235">Notes:—</emphasis>
According to Luer &amp; Hirtz (1992), the flowers of this species are distinguished by their densely redspiculate floral bracts, ovary and sepals that are borne by short peduncles (actually pseudopeduncles) usually less than three millimeters long, petals thickened and microscopically erose or cellular-capitate and ligulate lip with a pair or denticulate carinae. The most similar species is 
<taxonomicName id="41973CD8FFBF850CFD33FC25FCD1FC68" authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Schltr." box="[669,798,986,1012]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Myoxanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="24" pageNumber="235" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="herzogii">
<emphasis id="B4E39B49FFBF850CFD33FC25FCD1FC68" box="[669,798,986,1012]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="235">M. herzogii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which shares most of the same diagnostic features except for the denticulate carinae of the lip.
</paragraph>
